[[sn:Kōshin-tō]] [[ja:庚申塔]] {{translated page|ja|庚申塔|version=103910840|comment=Imported full ja history}}

{{Citation needed|date=January 2025}} '''Kōshintō''' (庚申塔), also called '''Kōshinzuka''' (庚申塚), are stone towers or mounds originating from the [[Taoism|Daoist]]-inspired [[Kōshin faith]] (庚申信仰) brought to Japan from [[China]]. These towers are often erected to commemorate the Completion tier 2]] (庚申待, Kōshin-machi) held 18 times over three years. Because they were built atop mounds, they are also referred to as '''Kōshinzuka''', and due to the associated rituals, they are also called '''Kōshin Kuyōtō''' (庚申供養塔).
The [[Kōshin vigil]] involves staying awake through the night of [[Kōshin]] days to prevent the [[Sanshi]] (三尸虫), parasitic spirits believed to inhabit the human body, from reporting one’s misdeeds to the [[Heavenly Emperor]]. To avert this, people worship deities such as [[Sarutahiko]], [[Batō Kannon]], or [[Shōmen Kongō]] and perform devotional or celebratory activities.
The design of Kōshintō varies widely. Common motifs include [[three wise monkeys]] ("see no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil"), symbols associated with the [[zodiac sign]] of the monkey ([[申]]), or inscriptions of participant names from the vigil. [[Shōmen Kongō]] images, regarded as the patron deity of Kōshin in [[Buddhism]], or depictions of [[Sarutahiko]] in [[Shinto]] contexts, are frequently featured. Some Kōshintō along roads also serve as waymarkers or are erected as [[Dōsojin]] to protect villages, often placed at boundaries or intersections.
Kōshintō can be found throughout Japan, except [[Okinawa Prefecture]], with significant regional variations in numbers. For example, many exist in the [[Kantō region]], while they are less common in [[Kyoto]] and [[Osaka]] within the [[Kansai region]], despite these areas’ centrality in Japan’s religious history. The oldest surviving Kōshintō is a [[Kōshin banpi]] (庚申板碑) from [[1471]] in [[Saitama Prefecture]]. The earliest depiction of [[Shōmen Kongō]] is found on a [[Fukui Prefecture]] stone from [[1647]], while a wooden statue from [[Nara]]’s [[Tōdai-ji]] dates back to the [[Kamakura period]].
== History == The widespread construction of Kōshintō began in the early [[Edo period]] (early [[17th century]]). Early towers featured diverse deities such as [[Amida Buddha]] and [[Jizō]], but [[Shōmen Kongō]] later became the dominant figure. In the mid to late Edo period, inscriptions with just "Kōshintō" or "Kōshin" became increasingly common.
In [[Hyōgo Prefecture]], 77 stone Kōshintō have been documented in [[Toyooka]]’s [[Tanto]] district. Most date from the [[18th century]] to the early [[20th century]]<ref>『但東の庚申塔』但東町教育委員会, 1999, pp.6-7</ref>.
During the [[Meiji period]], the government criticized Kōshin beliefs as superstition, leading to the removal of many towers, especially along roads. Later, urban development during Japan’s [[postwar economic boom]] further reduced their numbers. Remaining Kōshintō are often found in temple grounds or private lands, where they were relocated for preservation.
== Gallery == <gallery> Image:庚申塔 UP200607171855.JPG|Kōshintō in [[Umi, Fukuoka]]. Image:庚申塔 UP200607171910.JPG|Kōshintō in [[Itoshima, Fukuoka]]. Image:出石町奥山の庚申塔と地蔵.jpg|Kōshintō in [[Izushi, Hyōgo]]. Image:Koshin pillar.jpg|[[Shōmen Kongō]] and three wise monkeys ([[Narashino, Chiba]]). Image:Hyaku Kōshin.JPG|Cluster of Kōshintō ([[Fukaya, Saitama]]). </gallery>
== 3D Models == <gallery> File:庚申塔（八雲神社）.stl|Kōshintō from [[Yagumo Shrine]] (1770, [[Shizuoka Prefecture]]). </gallery>
